The patch leaves timestamp validation gaps that allow out-of-contract edge times through the new integer/ISO boundary. These can surface as malformed consolidation wire values or silently misinterpreted validity instants.

Full review comments:

- [P2] Reject pre-year-0000 edge epochs explicitly — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1892-1894
  For governed SDK writes with `t_valid`/`t_invalid` below `MIN_RENDERABLE_EPOCH` but still inside SQLite's broader unixepoch render range (for example `-62167219201`), this check succeeds because `strftime(..., 'unixepoch')` returns strings such as `-001-12-31T23:59:59Z` instead of NULL. Those values are outside the documented years 0000..=9999 wire range and can later be emitted to the consolidation harness in a form the inbound normalizer/provider may reject, so the write boundary should enforce the declared min/max range rather than renderability alone.

- [P2] Validate ISO syntax before using SQLite date parsing — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1824-1827
  When the BYO-LLM extractor or consolidation boundary sends numeric-looking strings such as `"2451545.0"` or `"0"`, SQLite treats them as Julian-day values and `strftime('%s', ?)` returns an epoch instead of NULL. That means malformed non-ISO wire timestamps are accepted and stored as unrelated instants despite the new hard-reject contract, which can incorrectly mark fallback/validity times; add an ISO-8601 shape check before delegating to SQLite.
